This miscompilation happens in `llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp`. The specific code that performs this transformation is within `SimplifySelectInst`. The logic is as follows:
```cpp
// select (icmp eq X, Y), X, Y -> Y
if (LHS == TVal && RHS == FVal)
  return FVal;
// select (icmp eq X, Y), Y, X -> X
if (LHS == FVal && RHS == TVal)
  return FVal;
```
This logic is sound for integers but not for pointers under models with provenance. To fix this, I need to disable this optimization for pointer types. I can do this by adding a check `!LHS->getType()->isPointerTy()` to the conditions. `LHS` is one of the operands of the `icmp`, and in this pattern, all operands (`LHS`, `RHS`, `TVal`, `FVal`) will have the same type.

I will use `sed` to modify the two `if` conditions in `llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp` to include this check.

```bash
sed -i -e 's/if (LHS == TVal && RHS == FVal)/if (LHS == TVal \&\& RHS == FVal \&\& !LHS->getType()->isPointerTy())/' -e 's/if (LHS == FVal && RHS == TVal)/if (LHS == FVal \&\& RHS == TVal \&\& !LHS->getType()->isPointerTy())/' llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp
```

