My previous patch was too aggressive and caused a regression in `select-icmp.ll`. The patch disabled `simplifySelectWithEquivalence` for all pointer equality comparisons, but this optimization is valid in some cases, such as when one of the operands is a null pointer. The original issue is about pointers that have the same address but different provenance, which is not a concern when comparing against `null`.

To fix this, I need to revert my previous change and apply a more targeted patch. The core issue is that `simplifySelectWithEquivalence` incorrectly assumes that if `icmp eq %a, %b` is true, `%a` and `%b` are interchangeable. This is false for pointers with different provenance.

The function `simplifySelectWithEquivalence` uses `simplifyWithOpsReplaced` to perform the substitution. I will modify `simplifySelectWithEquivalence` to prevent this substitution for pointer types. Specifically, I will add a check `!TrueVal->getType()->isPointerTy()` before the calls to `simplifyWithOpsReplaced`. This will disable the optimization for all pointer types, which is what I tried before, but this time I'm targeting the `simplifyWithOpsReplaced` calls directly inside `simplifySelectWithEquivalence`.

After re-examining the code, a better approach is to prevent `simplifySelectWithEquivalence` from being called for pointers in the first place from its caller `simplifySelectWithICmpCond`, but only when neither operand is a constant pointer (like null). This is more precise.

The call to `simplifySelectWithEquivalence` is inside `simplifySelectWithICmpCond`. I will add a condition to skip this call if the comparison is between two non-constant pointers.

```cpp
// In simplifySelectWithICmpCond:
if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) {
  // The following equivalence-based simplification is not valid for pointers
  // unless one of them is a constant. If they are both variable pointers,
  // they may have different provenance but compare equal.
  if (CmpLHS->getType()->isPointerTy() && !isa<Constant>(CmpLHS) &&
      !isa<Constant>(CmpRHS))
    return nullptr;

  if (Value *V = simplifySelectWithEquivalence({{CmpLHS, CmpRHS}}, TrueVal,
                                               FalseVal, Q, MaxRecurse))
// ...
```

This seems like the correct logic. It fixes the original bug without breaking existing valid optimizations for pointers involving constants. I will now apply this change using `sed`.

```bash
sed -i $'/if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) {/a \\\n    // The following equivalence-based simplification is not valid for pointers\\\n    // unless one of them is a constant. If they are both variable pointers,\\\n    // they may have different provenance but compare equal.\\\n    if (CmpLHS->getType()->isPointerTy() && !isa<Constant>(CmpLHS) &&\\\n        !isa<Constant>(CmpRHS))\\\n      return nullptr;\\\n' llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp
```

